:: John Mbiti’s (1969)\  {"position":"375,700","size":"100,100"}
The critical texts to be used for the religious analysis of the above texts are first, John Mbiti’s (1969) // “African Religions and Philosophy”. //This work explores various dimensions of African traditional religion. The book focuses on the traditional African religion’s beliefs, practices and values.  


:: Kwame Anthony Appiah (1992) {"position":"1250,200","size":"100,100"}
 //African identity and the post-colonial Challenge//
 explores the challenges of identity formation in post-colonial Africa. The text argues that a nuanced understanding of the continent’s diverse cultural traditions and histories is necessary for developing a cohesive African identity. 


:: Mbembe Achille (2002) {"position":"1100,100","size":"100,100"}
//The Politics of selfhood //

examines how African individuals and communities navigate multiple and sometimes conflicting identities in an environment of rapid social and political change.  



:: Obi Cyril (2003) {"position":"900,100","size":"100,100"}
// Identity, Conflict, and Reconstruction in Africa//

This paper contends that the relationship between identity, conflict and reconstruction in Africa can only be carried out by focusing on the locally driven approach to conflict resolution and recovery is essential for sustainable peace and development.  



:: Religion {"position":"600,300","size":"100,100"}
In this analysis we shall use Joseph Casely Hayford's Ethiopia Unbound (1911). Casely Hayford painstakingly asserts the place of African traditional religion in the face of Christianity. He uses various analogies to reiterate the Akan belief in God. The author illustrates the imposing nature of colonialism in Christianity as an agency to impose other belief systems (Christianity and Islam) among African people.  

