:: Salim Aga {"position":"1100,600","size":"100,100"}
// “Africa considered in its social and political condition”//
 The last text for this work is Salim Aga’s “Africa considered in its social and political condition” though this text does not directly discuss identity in the broader sense of the word, it does highlight the impact of African cultural identity, and through this text, we are espoused to ways in which African societies navigate or negotiate their cultural identities in the face of colonization.  


:: Samuel Ajayi et al. {"position":"900,525","size":"100,100"}
// “Letter to Henry Venn; Letter to Samuel Ajayi Crowther”.//
 Both letters by Samuel Ajayi Crowther unearth the place of colonization among African people. Through the first letter, we gain insight into how African society knowingly or unknowingly reinforced structures of colonization. Through the second letter, we are made to know about existing hierarchical structures and how existing ones were marginalized over newer ones. The sent letter to his son exposes Crowther’s ideals in meandering the ideals of colonization: empowerment of the agency of education.


:: Samuel Johnson et al. (1875). 2022 {"position":"675,675","size":"100,100"}
//“Sick and Dying Christians in Yoruba”//. In this work, Johnson brings out the inner conflict and difficulties that Christian converts faced as they sought traditional or orthodox medicine for various illnesses. 


:: Terence Ranger(1983) {"position":"125,550","size":"100,100"}
//“The invention of Tradition Revisited: The case of colonial Africa//. This text explores how colonial powers created and imposed new traditional and cultural practices on African societies and how these practices continue to shape African cultures and identities. 


:: Walter Rodney(1982) {"position":"100,400","size":"100,100"}
//How Europe Underdeveloped Africa//. This book is a detailed analysis of the impact of European colonization on African countries and argues that the exploitation of African resources and people was central to the development of Europe’s capitalist economy.  


:: Weah Bye {"position":"200,0","size":"100,100"}
//“‘The Liberian War. To the Editor of the Times” //is a narrative that recounts the presence of foreign nationals settled in Liberia, including Germans, French, English and  Americans. These individuals’ presence is due to colonial activities in the West African sub-region. The narrator’s statement: how could I venture to raise my puny arm against the British Government as to perpetrate.... such a black deed in murdering a British subject in defiance of British Power,” is pregnant with many revelations


